   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1816-08-04"/>August 4, 1816. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p> May I hope that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ArraF1">M. Arrago</persName>
               <lb/>
                    has not forgotten those<lb/>
                    three little English ladies<lb/>
                    the three sisters to whom<lb/>
                    he was so kind whenever<lb/>
                    he saw them at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BumfM1">Madame<lb/>
                        de Bumford's</persName>--at the <placeName>
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Ob-<lb/>
                            servatory</orig>
                     <reg>Observatory</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> - and at <placeName ref="./Personography.xml#Chamousey_XX">
                  <unclear>Chamousey</unclear>
               </placeName>
               <note type="certainty">Edgeworth's hand here is unclear if the place named is "Chamourey" or "Chamousey"</note>
               <lb/>
                    - Whenever they think of<lb/>
                    that delightful <unclear/> in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Switzerland#SZ">Switzerland</placeName>, the meeting<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ArraF1">M. Arrago</persName> at <placeName ref="./Personography.xml#Chamousey_XX">
                  <unclear>Chamousey</unclear>
               </placeName>
               <lb/>
                    comes to their mind as<lb/>
                    the most fortunate of all<lb/>
                    circumstances - and they<lb/>
                    feel most grateful for<lb/>
                    the happiness of having<lb/>
                    had so much of his <choice>
                  <orig>con-<lb/>
                        versation</orig>
                  <reg>conversation</reg>
               </choice> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>   Yet my dear Sir when<lb/>
                    we most enjoyed that <choice>
                  <orig>con-<lb/>
                        versation</orig>
                  <reg>conversation</reg>
               </choice>, we always had<lb/>
                    one regret mixed with<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page02.jpg"/> 
                    our great pleasure - When<lb/>
                    you were explaining to<lb/>
                    us the machinery &amp; <lb/>
                    instruments at the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris-Observatory_FR">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>obser-<lb/>
                        vatory</orig>
                     <reg>observatory</reg>
                  </choice> at Paris</placeName>, when you<lb/>
                    spoke of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Brinkley</persName> and<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WollW1">Wollaston</persName>, &amp; when at<lb/>
                    the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Glacier-de-Bossons_FR">glacier de Boissons</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    you were <del/>
               <lb/>
                    speaking of the polarity<lb/>
                    of light - &amp; when at the<lb/>
                    little inn at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#St-Martin_XX">S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Martin</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    you delighted us by your<lb/>
                    warm approbation of our<lb/>
                    friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beauforts</persName>
               <lb/>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">Karamania</title> - and when<lb/>
                    you mentioned with<lb/>
                    so much kindness my <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR1">father</persName>
               <lb/>
                    and inquired concerning<lb/>
                    various things that had<lb/>
                    occupied him in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <p> The improvement of our<lb/>
                    boys - the construction of<lb/>
                    our village spire, then &amp; <lb/>
                    MA 3617 (pg 1)<lb/>
               <note place="bottom">Added by library, not Maria Edgeworth</note>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page03.jpg"/> 
                    always when we were<lb/>
                    most delighted &amp; instructed<lb/>
                    by your conversation we<lb/>
                    regretted that a dear<lb/>
                    brother of ours, was not<lb/>
                    present - A brother whose<lb/>
                    ardent desire to improve<lb/>
                    himself, whose love of<lb/>
                    science, whose scientific<lb/>
                    pursuits, profession and<lb/>
                    knowledge qualify him<lb/>
                    so <del>much</del> well to value<lb/>
                    that conversation &amp; to<lb/>
                    whom it would not only<lb/>
                    be of the greatest pleasure<lb/>
                    but of permanent service<lb/>
                    in his <add>future</add> professional life.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>   Permit me now to<lb/>
                    present this brother to<lb/>
                    you - He is young you<lb/>
                    see -and can as yet have<lb/>
                    done but little - he has<lb/>
                    however done something<lb/>
                    - It was he who <choice>
                  <orig>superintend
                        -ed</orig>
                  <reg>superintended</reg>
               </choice> the raising of that spire<lb/>
                    - It as he who assisted<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page04.jpg"/>    
                    in the survey of those Irish<lb/>
                    bogs - And who has <choice>
                  <orig>complet-<lb/>
                        ed</orig>
                  <reg>completed</reg>
               </choice> a trigonometrical survey<lb/>
                    of large districts in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    -- He has been <choice>
                  <orig>distinguish<lb/>
                        -ed</orig>
                  <reg>distinguished</reg>
               </choice> and I may say is beloved<lb/>
                    as a favorite pupil, by him<lb/>
                    whom you named to me<lb/>
                    as the man of science who<lb/>
                    does most honor to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
               <lb/>
                    - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrinJ1">Doctor Brinkley</persName>--<lb/>
                    He is <del/>
               <del>the</del> not only<lb/>
                    nearly connected by family<lb/>
                    ties with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beauforts</persName>
               <lb/>
                    the author of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">Karamania</title>
               <lb/>
                    but he is his chosen friend.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WollW1">Wollaston</persName> has honored<lb/>
                    him with much of his <choice>
                  <orig>inti-
                        -mate</orig>
                  <reg>intimate</reg>
               </choice> conversation on <choice>
                  <orig>scien-
                            -tific</orig>
                  <reg>scientific</reg>
               </choice> subjects, and I may<lb/>
                    say that all of our men of<lb/>
                    science who have seen him<lb/>
                    have prophecied favorably<lb/>
                    of his future professional<lb/>
                    application &amp; success.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> His profession is that of<lb/>
                    a civil engineer -- the object<lb/>
                    of his present tour to the<lb/>
                    continent is to acquire<lb/>
               <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page05.jpg"/> 
                    knowledge &amp; to improve himself on<lb/>
                    every subject connected with that <choice>
                  <orig>pro-
                        -fession</orig>
                  <reg>profession</reg>
               </choice> -- You will oblige me in the<lb/>
                    most essential manner if you will<lb/>
                    assist him in making himself <choice>
                  <orig>acquaint
                        -ed</orig>
                  <reg>acquainted</reg>
               </choice> with the objects best worth <add>his</add> seeing<lb/>
                    in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> as an engineer and an <choice>
                  <orig>astro-
                        -nomer</orig>
                  <reg>astronomer</reg>
               </choice> -- You will find his thirst for<lb/>
                    knowledge of all kinds ardent - Who<lb/>
                    can better satisfy it?<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> He will be grateful for any kindness<lb/>
                    you shew him - He will not see the<lb/>
               <unclear>most</unclear> celebrated talents in France<lb/>
               <unclear>W</unclear> eyes of English national <unclear>j</unclear>
               <lb/>
               <unclear>I think</unclear> in short that you will like him<lb/>
               <unclear>and</unclear> I will say no more -- except<lb/>
                    that my sisters Fanny &amp; Harriet will<lb/>
                    be delighted if you do -- &amp; so shall I --<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
                    Your obliged<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Rue-St-Jacques_FR">Rue S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Jacques<lb/>
                        N<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>. 175</placeName>
               <note place="bottom">Written in a hand different from Maria Edgeworth's</note>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p/>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
               <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157753_page06.jpg"/>
               <address>
                        a<lb/>
                        Monsieur<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ArraF1">Monsieur Arrago</persName>
                  <lb/>
                        a l'Observatoire<lb/>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
                  <addrLine/>
               </address>
            </closer>
